On Fri, 18 Feb 2005 02:42:20 -0500, J. B. Rainsberger
&lt;jbrains@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  Chris Dollin wrote:
&gt;  &gt; On Thursday 17 February 2005 15:18, Mike Clark wrote:
&gt;  &gt;  &gt; I like how you think, Todd.  :-)
&gt;  &gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;  &gt; I don&#39;t know the history behind the design decision to use static
&gt;  &gt;  &gt; methods in Assert, but I&#39;d love to know.
&gt;  &gt; 
&gt;  &gt; My *guess* would be that this allows them to be used without
&gt;  &gt; having to inherit from, or have to hand an instance of,
&gt;  &gt; Assert.
&gt;  &gt; 
&gt;  &gt; Like, you want to put a JUnit-style assertion in a piece of code
&gt;  &gt; that already exists.
&gt;  
&gt;  I would have preferred they use the Java logging idiom:
&gt;  
&gt;  class MyClass {
&gt;       private static final Assert assert = Assert.getInstance();
&gt;       ...
&gt;  }
&gt;  
&gt;  Now the assert*() methods can be instance-level.
